 Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel de Basset was born in 1175, in Brackley, Northamptonshire, England, her father, Robert Basset, was 25 and her mother, Beatrice de HARCOURT, was 24. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Wolvey. She died in 1224, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1175–1224":"1175–1224","1170–1256":"1170–1256","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1151–Male":"1151–Surnud","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","1151":"1151","1170":"1170","Brackley, Northamptonshire, England":"Brackley, Northamptonshire, England","Stanstead, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1175–1224":"1175–1224","1170–1256":"1170–1256","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1151–Male":"1151–Kuollut","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","1151":"1151","1170":"1170","Brackley, Northamptonshire, England":"Brackley, Northamptonshire, England","Stanstead, Essex, England":"